INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'f9db95d5-611f-4055-ad5f-47d75ba5c43b',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Bicep Destroy Safety — Lifecycle Rules to Prevent Accidental Resource Deletion$escape$,
  $escape$Bicep's `existing` keyword and the `@sealed()` decorator protect against drift, but the real guard against accidental deletion is the resource `lock` resource type and the `resourceLock` resource provider. Deploy a `Microsoft.Authorization/locks` child resource with `level: 'CanNotDelete'` to block deletions even from contributors with full RBAC. For stateful resources — Storage Accounts, Key Vaults, PostgreSQL Flexible Servers — this is non-negotiable.

Beyond locks, use `dependsOn` deliberately: if a database lock depends on the database resource, Bicep tears down the lock before the DB during `az deployment group delete`, which is the correct destruction order. Pair this with `az deployment group what-if --mode Complete` before any Complete-mode deploy — Complete mode deletes resources absent from the template, so what-if is your last line of defense. Set `'Complete'` mode only in pipelines behind a manual approval gate. For incremental day-to-day deploys, omit `--mode` entirely to default to `Incremental`.$escape$,
  $escape$resource storageAccount 'Microsoft.Storage/storageAccounts@2023-01-01' = {
  name: storageAccountName
  location: location
  sku: { name: 'Standard_LRS' }
  kind: 'StorageV2'
}

resource storageLock 'Microsoft.Authorization/locks@2020-05-01' = {
  name: '${storageAccountName}-delete-lock'
  scope: storageAccount
  properties: {
    level: 'CanNotDelete'
    notes: 'Prevent accidental deletion of production storage.'
  }
}$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
